[Server thread/INFO] [cy.jdkdigital.productivefarming.ProductiveFarming/]: speed:12.5 growth:3 max:false state:Block{productivefarming:wheat}[age=5]
[Server thread/INFO] [cy.jdkdigital.productivefarming.ProductiveFarming/]: grow

- Wastes disk space and I/O  
- Impractical to share logs for debugging  

Would appreciate a way to control or reduce this logging. Thanks!

![medium](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/medium-priority.svg)

This broad `except Exception` block catches all potential errors during client initialization and test execution but immediately exits without logging any details about the error. This makes it difficult to diagnose failures. It would be more helpful to log the exception before exiting so the cause of the failure is visible in the CI logs.

```suggestion
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"E2E test failed with an exception: {e}")
        exit(1)
```

issue.title: Sorting out the XG LSB problem

type.name: Feature
type.description: A request, idea, or new functionality

issue.body:
### Problem

A discussion started between me and @sylvia-leaf via email:


> Hi Sylvia,
> 
> I'm writing about considering adding limited bank LSB to spessasynth_core's master. One user of spessafont mentioned the lack of LSB in DLS (which is supported) and since 4.0 is planning to be the last breaking change API, I could take the opportunity to introduce bank LSB.
> 
> I think of modifying BasicPreset like following:
> 
>  - bank -> bankMSB
>  -  new field: bankLSB
>  -  bank 128 would instead be a bool "drumPreset". These drums are used for GM and GS (XG has 127)
>  -  another bool called "hasBankLSB" which would be false for sf2 and true for dls. If false, the XG hacks are enabled. > If true, regular bank behavior is used.
> 
> What do you think? Let me know.
> 
> Regards,
> spessasus

> Dear Spessasus,
> 
> Thanks for the heads up! I think that it would be great to see limited bank LSB support in SpessaSynth 4.0 independent of SFe.
> 
> I've got a few questions:
> - What LSB functions do you plan on using?
> - How will they be accessible in SF2?
> - What would I need to do?
> 
> If 4.0 adds LSB support, then I will work on removing the existing LSB support from the reference implementation when updating it to use TypeScript. This may also fix the drum kit bugs. Additionally, I'll add any SFe specific features that are not included in SpessaSynth 4.0.
> 
> Yours sincerely,
> 
> Sylvia (they/she)

> Hi Sylvia,
> 
> Thanks for your response.
> 
> Addressing your questions:
> 
> - I'm hoping to make LSB work as it is now. That is: both XG and GS. Currently the system is built around SF2 and DLS adapts to that: https://github.com/spessasus/spessasynth_core/blob/660f910f0f421166eefe98b8e4150b80d7d976fb/src/soundfont/dls/dls_preset.js#L24-L38
> - The plan is to instead adapt SF2 to DLS. SF2 would have its bank LSB and MSB be equal (except for 64, 120, 126 127 and 128), and the bank selection logic would first look for an exact match, then LSB (if it's not zero), then MSB match. That way I think it could work as it currently does.
> - Alternatively I could keep bank LSB as 0 and have a toggle "hasBankMSB" I mentioned earlier to apply XG hacks, but that would be messy with sflist mixing the two and converting to dls would break it (DLS has bank LSB so spessasynth would see that it's zero explicitly, therefore no hacks would be applied)
> - As for what would you need to do: I think that the only thing you'd need would be adding read/write support for SFe and removing the other LSB code. I'd have to take care of the hacks :-)
> 
> And one more thing: I've mentioned in my last email that I think replacing bank 128 with drum toggle would be a good idea. SF2 would just write bank 128 when it's on. With spessafont i could then change the UI to allow entering either 0-127 or toggling a drum preset. These drums would be for GS/GM (as these don't have bank numbers for them, only special flags). And same during reading: if a drum preset is encountered, both LSB and MSB will be set to zero. Not sure about XG though. I think we could treat them like normal presets, but if they are missing, force the channel to drums. It's a bit messy, but it is what it is.
> 
> What do you think? Do you have a better solution? Please let me know.
> 
> Regards,
> spessasus (Stanley if you prefer)

I'm sharing it because other members of the team (like @stgiga) might have better ideas and it's important

As written above, I'd like to add bankLSB as the part of the new 4.0 API to spessasynth_core's master, allowing full DLS LSB support.

The problem is with SF2s and bank LSB hacks for XG.

Currently it works like this:
- Bank MSBs 120, 126 and 127 flag the channel as drums in XG mode. This causes the program to look for the XG drum preset with the given bank, otherwise falling back to GM/GS banks (128)
- All other bank MSBs in XG are ignored and bank LSB is selected for the SF2 bank number. A notable exception is bank 64 standing for XG SFX. It's used instead of bank LSB for the selection.

The main problem with the current API is that **it's built around SF2's single bank number rather can DLS's full bank specifier.** For example, DLS [flattens its bank numbers to just one](https://github.com/spessasus/spessasynth_core/blob/660f910f0f421166eefe98b8e4150b80d7d976fb/src/soundfont/dls/dls_preset.js#L24-L38) to work with this.

### Description

My proposal for this is reworking the program to work on both bank numbers and adding a proper drum flag.

And for the XG problem I think I have an even better solution than in that email: **Make two presets!**

That is: `001:080 Square` becomes two presets: `000:001:080 Square` and `001:000:080 Square`.

Exceptions from this (no copying, only MSB): 
- 64 (XG SFX).
- 120 (GM2 Drums)
- 126 (XG SFX Drums)
- 127 (XG Drums)

These are not copied because we only need the LSB presets for XG and these don't use LSB.

For SF2 writing, it would look if a 000:XXX:YYY preset has a XXX:000:YYY copy and discard it, otherwise flatten the bank. SFe editors could always warn about this.

Here's why I think it would work:
- Regardless of if the bank was meant to be for XG LSB or for GS MSB, both work
- Avoids redundant copies of XG presets that don't need them
- SF2 banks converted to SFe and then back would still preserve the LSB banks

One problem with this approach is the duplicate names. SF2 spec says:

> The ASCII character field achPresetName contains the name of the preset expressed in ASCII, with unused terminal
characters filled with zero valued bytes. Preset names are case sensitive. A unique name should always be assigned to each
preset in the SoundFont compatible bank to enable identification. However, if a bank is read containing the erroneous state
of presets with identical names, the presets should not be discarded. They should either be preserved as read or preferably
uniquely renamed.

So I guess it's alright?

What do you think?

We need to sort this out as ensuring SF2s made for both XG and GS working like they did before is extremely important for SFe. It can't be a downgrade.

@sylvia-leaf @stgiga @Falcosoft @davy7125 @Cacodemon345 do you have any ideas? (wish GH had a way to ping all members of the team automatically)

### Alternatives

_No response_

### Additional info

https://musical-artifacts.com/artifacts/5826

This SF2 is very handy for testing the XG hacks. Also GeneralUserGS/gm.dls for testing the XG fallback to GS drums)

https://musical-artifacts.com/artifacts/6094

And this one has banks that are supposed to be XG LSB banks.

issue.title: cpufeatures: do not prevent inlining
issue.body:
I suspect that `#[inline(never)]` is used for performance reasons, but maybe something like `#[cold]` is sufficient for the same purpose? `#[cold]` is what `once_cell` is using in performance-sensitive places for example.

It is causing issues for me with https://github.com/dtolnay/no-panic, which relies on inlining and `cpufeatures` is the only thing using `#[inline(never)]` in multiple cases where platform-dependent code is present.
